    question: 'Compare anthropometry (Bertillon system) with fingerprint system for personal identification. Why was anthropometry replaced?',
    answer: `<h4>Anthropometry (Bertillon System) — 1879</h4>
<p>Developed by Alphonse Bertillon (France) for identification of habitual criminals.</p>
<h4>Principle (2 Postulates)</h4>
<ol><li>After 21 years of age, body part measurements DO NOT change significantly</li>
<li>The ratio of body part sizes varies considerably between individuals</li></ol>
<h4>Records Maintained</h4>
<ul><li><strong>Descriptive data:</strong> iris colour, hair, complexion, shape of nose / chin / ears, full-face + right-profile photographs</li>
<li><strong>Body marks:</strong> moles, birthmarks, tattoo marks, scars</li>
<li><strong>11 Body measurements:</strong> standing height, sitting height, head length, head width, ear length, ear width, span of outstretched arms, length of left middle finger, length of left little finger, length of left forearm + hand, length of left foot</li></ul>
<h4>Comparison: Anthropometry vs Fingerprint</h4>
<table><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Anthropometry (Bertillon)</th><th>Fingerprints (Galton)</th></tr>
<tr><td>Year introduced</td><td>1879 (France)</td><td>1892 (England — Galton classified; Vucetich applied)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Principle</td><td>Body part measurements + ratios</td><td>Unique papillary ridge patterns</td></tr>
<tr><td>Applicable to</td><td>Adults only (&gt; 21 yr — measurements not yet stable in children)</td><td>All ages (form in 2nd-3rd month IUL, permanent for life)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Objectivity</td><td>SUBJECTIVE — measurement error common</td><td>OBJECTIVE — pattern matching</td></tr>
<tr><td>Equipment + manpower</td><td>Needs special instruments + trained staff</td><td>Simple — ink + paper; AFIS automated</td></tr>
<tr><td>Time</td><td>Lengthy</td><td>Quick</td></tr>
<tr><td>Twin discrimination</td><td>POOR (twins similar size)</td><td>EXCELLENT — individual even in monozygotic twins</td></tr>
<tr><td>Accuracy</td><td>Limited — overlaps common</td><td>Absolute — 1 in 64 billion identical</td></tr>
<tr><td>Crime scene applicability</td><td>None (need body present)</td><td>Latent prints at scene</td></tr>
<tr><td>Current status</td><td>★ <strong>OBSOLETE</strong> — replaced</td><td>★ Standard worldwide</td></tr></table>
<h4>Why Anthropometry Was Replaced</h4>
<ol><li><strong>Subjective error</strong> — different operators give different measurements</li>
<li><strong>Adult-only</strong> — useless for children &amp; growing adolescents</li>
<li><strong>Trained personnel + special instruments</strong> required</li>
<li><strong>Overlaps</strong> — different individuals can have similar measurements; not stand-alone</li>
<li><strong>Cannot be left at crime scene</strong> — no latent equivalent</li>
<li><strong>Twin problem</strong> — identical or fraternal twins have similar measurements</li>
<li><strong>Will West case (1903)</strong> — two prisoners at Leavenworth (US) with same name and identical Bertillon measurements but DIFFERENT fingerprints. This case effectively ended Bertillon\'s dominance.</li>
<li><strong>Fingerprints proved absolutely unique</strong> — even in monozygotic twins (NEET-PG 2019 Q5)</li></ol>
<h4>Conclusion</h4>
<p>The fingerprint system superseded anthropometry due to its objectivity, applicability to all ages, individuality even in twins, latent print recovery at crime scenes, and ease of automation (AFIS). Today, fingerprints + DNA + dental records form the "iron triangle" of primary identification per Interpol DVI standards.</p>`,
